{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2381"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2381"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.14,0.13,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2381"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39539"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43135"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man is admitted to hospital presenting with trouble breathing due to an exacerbation of his long-standing congestive heart failure. Three days after initiating medical treatment for his heart failure, he develops abnormal blood and urine laboratory results. His blood results show a raised creatinine of 150 umol/L (60 - 115) that was previously normal, and a urea of 16 mmol/L (3.0 - 6.0). His urinalysis show a decrease in urine sodium of 15 mmol/L (\u0026lt;20mmol/L) and a high urine osmolality of 600 mOsm/kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history that includes congestive heart failure, benign prostatic hyperplasia and osteoarthritis. His pre-hospital medications include regular ibuprofen and simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he does not appear in discomfort or pain. His vital signs show a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min, respiratory rate 16/min and oxygen saturation of 97% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease NSAID medication","Limit oral intake and fluid restriction","Administer furosemide","Administer perindopril","Administer spironolactone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has developed an acute kidney injury (AKI) secondary to hypovolaemia due to the loop diuretics (furosemide) used for his congestive heart failure treatment in the hospital. This patient may have a pre-existing reduced renal blood flow due to systolic heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rise in creatinine and the disproportionate rise of urea as compared to creatinine (i.e. urea:creatinine ratio greater than 20:1) would indicate pre-renal AKI. Excessive diuretics leading to volume depletion and subsequently a reduced renal blood flow will activate the renal-angiotensin-aldosterone-system (RAAS). Aldosterone causes sodium and water retention to maintain GFR and systemic blood pressure. This leads to the raised urea:creatinine ratio due to the increase in urea reabsorption, and raised urine osmolarity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo reduce further insult to the AKI, it is important to r\u003Cstrong\u003Eemove any drugs that may be nephrotoxic i.e. NSAIDs\u003C/strong\u003E, gentamicin, ACE inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELimiting oral intake, fluid restriction and administering furosemide would further exacerbate this prerenal AKI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAngiotensin blockage drugs such as perindopril and spironolactone should be avoided as these medications alter the kidney\u0027s ability to autoregulate blood flow during states of decreased renal blood flow - this would commonly exacerbate prerenal AKI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nephrotoxic drugs should be avoided in patients with acute kidney injury"],"references":["Grams ME, Estrella MM, Coresh J, et al. Fluid balance, diuretic use, and mortality in acute kidney injury. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol 2011; 6:966.","Lameire N, Van Biesen W, Vanholder R. Acute renal failure. Lancet 2005; 365:417."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39539"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2381"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39539"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T14:36:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T14:36:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2381"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54066"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t